<h2>Class 6 Overview</h2>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Instructor Prep</div>Students often confuse "detailed" with "correct" &mdash; a Class 1 estimate can still be wrong if it's priced against the wrong scope. The whole second half of this lesson exists to break that assumption. Bring a calculator or have students use phone calculators for Activity #1. Pre-load a blank quantity takeoff sheet on the classroom screen to model the worked example live before releasing students into groups. Course runs Aug 25&ndash;Dec 3, 2026 (no class Nov 24&ndash;26, Thanksgiving break).</div>

<h3>Timed Lecture Outline</h3>
<div class="tl">
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:00&ndash;0:05 (5 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Hook &amp; Context</div><div class="tdesc">Real case: a $2.1M design-build project where a missing scope line (fire pump room finishes) surfaced during construction &mdash; not a math error, a scope-alignment failure. Ask: "Whose fault was this?"</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:05&ndash;0:15 (10 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Classes of Estimates</div><div class="tdesc">AACE five-class system (Class 5 &rarr; Class 1), typical accuracy ranges, and where each sits in the project lifecycle.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:15&ndash;0:30 (15 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Anatomy of a Detailed Estimate</div><div class="tdesc">Quantity takeoff &rarr; unit costs &rarr; direct costs &rarr; general conditions &rarr; OH&amp;P &rarr; contingency &rarr; total. Work the concrete slab example live on the board.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:30&ndash;0:40 (10 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Scope Alignment: WBS &harr; Estimate &harr; Scope Document</div><div class="tdesc">Every estimate line item should trace to a WBS element and a scope narrative line. Introduce the basis-of-estimate (BOE) and exclusions list as the estimator's insurance policy.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:40&ndash;0:55 (15 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Activity #1: "Build the Estimate"</div><div class="tdesc">Small groups take off quantities, price them, and roll up to a total price. Debrief on where teams landed and why totals differ.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:55&ndash;1:05 (10 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Scope Creep &amp; Contingency Stewardship</div><div class="tdesc">Causes of scope-estimate drift; PM levers (allowances, exclusions lists, contingency tracking). Bridge into the ethics tab.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">1:05&ndash;1:12 (7 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Activity #2: "The Scope Gap" &amp; Ethics Discussion</div><div class="tdesc">Pairs work through a disclosure dilemma using the PMI Code of Ethics.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">1:12&ndash;1:15 (3 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Wrap-Up &amp; Homework</div><div class="tdesc">Review key points, assign homework, preview Class 7 &mdash; turning the estimate into a bid package.</div></div>
</div>

<div class="callout cg"><strong>⚡ Teaching Tip</strong>The compounding-markup math is the single biggest "aha" moment in this lesson. Build the GC &rarr; OH&amp;P &rarr; contingency stack live on the board, one multiplier at a time &mdash; it lands better built up than shown all at once, and it pre-empts the most common student error (adding percentages instead of compounding them).</div>
</div>
