<h2>Lecture Notes &mdash; Estimating, Cost Planning &amp; Scope Alignment</h2>

<h3>Why Estimating Comes Before Everything Else Financial</h3>
<p>Every budget decision, every owner go/no-go decision, and every contractor bid decision depends on an estimate. An estimate is the dollar expression of scope, produced against a schedule assumption, at a defined level of risk.</p>
<div class="callout cb"><strong>🔑 Key Concept</strong>An estimate is only as good as the scope definition behind it. The math is the easy part &mdash; confirming what is actually included is the hard part, and it's where CMs add the most value.</div>

<h3>Classes of Estimates (AACE International Framework)</h3>
<p>AACE International's Recommended Practice 17R-97 (generic) and 56R-08 (building and general construction) define a five-class system that ranks estimates by their level of project definition &mdash; not by who prepared them or how much effort went in.</p>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Talking Point</div>"Estimate class is a property of the information available, not the project itself. A rushed Class 5 estimate done for a fully-designed project is still a Class 5 estimate if it's based on square-footage historical data instead of the actual drawings in hand."</div>
<div class="ot"><table>
<colgroup><col style="width:12%"><col style="width:22%"><col style="width:18%"><col style="width:20%"><col style="width:28%"></colgroup>
<thead><tr><th>Class</th><th>CM Industry Name</th><th>Project Definition</th><th>Typical Accuracy*</th><th>Typical Basis</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><span class="badge c5">Class 5</span></td><td>Order of Magnitude / ROM</td><td>0&ndash;2%</td><td>-50% / +100%</td><td>Historical $/SF, capacity curves</td></tr>
<tr><td><span class="badge c4">Class 4</span></td><td>Conceptual / Schematic</td><td>1&ndash;15%</td><td>-30% / +50%</td><td>Schematic design, assemblies pricing</td></tr>
<tr><td><span class="badge c3">Class 3</span></td><td>Design Development / Budget</td><td>10&ndash;40%</td><td>-20% / +30%</td><td>DD drawings, partial specs, sub budget quotes</td></tr>
<tr><td><span class="badge c2">Class 2</span></td><td>Construction Documents / Bid</td><td>30&ndash;75%</td><td>-15% / +20%</td><td>90&ndash;100% CDs, detailed takeoff, firm sub quotes</td></tr>
<tr><td><span class="badge c1">Class 1</span></td><td>Definitive / Check Estimate</td><td>50&ndash;100%</td><td>-10% / +15%</td><td>Fully bid, signed subcontracts, GMP reconciliation</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--muted);">*Generic AACE 17R-97 ranges shown for teaching purposes; AACE 56R-08 (building/general construction) provides construction-industry-specific input-maturity tables. Ranges assume contingency has been appropriately addressed &mdash; roughly 80% of projects should fall within the stated band.</p>
<div class="callout cgr"><strong>✅ CM Application</strong>A CM at Risk project typically re-estimates at each design milestone &mdash; SD (Class 4), DD (Class 3), and CDs (Class 2) &mdash; narrowing the range each time until the GMP is set on a Class 2/1 estimate.</div>

<h3>Anatomy of a Detailed Cost Estimate</h3>
<div class="card">
<h4>The Build-Up, Line by Line</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Quantity takeoff (QTO):</strong> Measure quantities directly from drawings/specs.</li>
<li><strong>Unit costs:</strong> Apply a $/unit rate built from material + labor + equipment.</li>
<li><strong>Direct costs:</strong> Sum of all quantity &times; unit-cost extensions.</li>
<li><strong>Indirect costs / general conditions (GCs):</strong> Project-level costs &mdash; supervision, temp facilities, safety, permits, insurance.</li>
<li><strong>Overhead &amp; profit (OH&amp;P):</strong> Home-office overhead recovery plus contractor markup.</li>
<li><strong>Contingency:</strong> Reserve for known-unknowns within the defined scope.</li>
</ol>
<p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Total Estimate = Direct Costs + General Conditions + OH&amp;P + Contingency</strong></p>
</div>

<h3>Worked Example &mdash; Concrete Slab-on-Grade Takeoff</h3>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Work This Live</div>Walk this example on the whiteboard before releasing students to Activity #1 &mdash; it is the exact structure they will repeat with different numbers.</div>
<div class="ot"><table>
<colgroup><col style="width:34%"><col style="width:16%"><col style="width:16%"><col style="width:17%"><col style="width:17%"></colgroup>
<thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Quantity</th><th>Unit</th><th>Unit Cost</th><th>Extension</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Slab-on-grade, 4" (100' &times; 60' = 6,000 SF)</td><td>74.1</td><td>CY</td><td>$185/CY</td><td>$13,709</td></tr>
<tr><td>6&times;6 W2.9&times;W2.9 WWF reinforcing</td><td>6,000</td><td>SF</td><td>$0.55/SF</td><td>$3,300</td></tr>
<tr><td>Vapor barrier, 10-mil poly</td><td>6,000</td><td>SF</td><td>$0.28/SF</td><td>$1,680</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fine grade &amp; compact subgrade</td><td>6,000</td><td>SF</td><td>$0.42/SF</td><td>$2,520</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Direct Cost Subtotal</strong></td><td colspan="3"></td><td><strong>$21,209</strong></td></tr>
<tr><td>General Conditions (8% of direct cost)</td><td colspan="3"></td><td>$1,697</td></tr>
<tr><td>Overhead &amp; Profit (12% of subtotal)</td><td colspan="3"></td><td>$2,749</td></tr>
<tr><td>Contingency (5% &mdash; Class 3 estimate)</td><td colspan="3"></td><td>$1,283</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Total Price</strong></td><td colspan="3"></td><td><strong>$26,938</strong></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Math Check</div>21,209 &times; 1.08 = 22,906 (GCs) &rarr; &times; 1.12 = 25,655 (OH&amp;P) &rarr; &times; 1.05 = 26,938 (Contingency). Markups compound sequentially, not additively &mdash; a common student error is adding 8% + 12% + 5% = 25% as a single multiplier, which understates the total.</div>

<h3>Scope Alignment: WBS &harr; Estimate &harr; Scope Document</h3>
<p>A cost estimate is only trustworthy if it can be traced in both directions: every dollar traces back to a scope item, and every scope item traces forward to a dollar. The Work Breakdown Structure (WBS) is the bridge between the two.</p>
<div class="card">
<h4>The Reconciliation Loop</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Scope document / OPR / narrative</strong> describes what the owner is buying, in words.</li>
<li><strong>WBS</strong> decomposes that scope into deliverable-oriented work packages.</li>
<li><strong>Cost estimate</strong> prices each WBS work package via quantity takeoff and unit costs.</li>
<li><strong>Basis of Estimate (BOE)</strong> documents assumptions, inclusions, and exclusions for every major line.</li>
<li><strong>Reconciliation:</strong> Walk the WBS against the estimate. Gaps in either direction are scope-alignment failures waiting to become change orders.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="callout cr"><strong>⚠ Where Gaps Hide</strong>Interface/scope-boundary items (who furnishes vs. who installs), permit and testing/commissioning costs, owner-furnished equipment hookups, and "assumed included" items across trade packages are the most common places a scope item disappears between design and estimate.</div>

<h3>Scope Creep &amp; Estimate&ndash;Budget Misalignment</h3>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="card"><h4>Common Causes</h4><ul><li>Incomplete design documents at time of estimate</li><li>Verbal owner direction not captured in writing</li><li>Allowances set too low with no vendor pricing yet</li><li>Missing exclusions list</li><li>Estimator/designer working from different drawing revisions</li></ul></div>
<div class="card"><h4>PM Prevention Strategies</h4><ul><li>Require a written Basis of Estimate with exclusions list</li><li>Track contingency drawdown by cause, not just dollars</li><li>Use allowances for real-but-undefined scope</li><li>Reconcile estimate against WBS at every milestone</li><li>Document all direction in writing</li></ul></div>
</div>

<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Talking Point</div>"A perfectly calculated estimate built on the wrong scope is still a wrong number. Ask students: if your math is flawless but you priced the wrong drawing revision, is your estimate 'accurate'? That question is where scope alignment becomes memorable."</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="tab-terms" class="tab-content">
<div class="pw">
<h2>Key Terms &mdash; Class 6</h2>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Note</div>Student edition has definitions blank for note-taking. These are the complete definitions for your reference.</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="card"><h4>Quantity Takeoff (QTO)</h4><p>The process of measuring quantities of materials, labor, and equipment directly from drawings and specifications to support pricing.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Unit Cost</h4><p>The cost per unit of measure (SF, CY, LF, EA) for an item of work, built up from material, labor, and equipment costs.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Direct Costs</h4><p>Costs directly attributable to the physical construction &mdash; labor, material, and equipment for specific work items, from the quantity takeoff.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Indirect Costs / General Conditions</h4><p>Project-level costs not tied to a specific quantity of work: supervision, temporary facilities, safety, permits, insurance, project office.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Overhead &amp; Profit (OH&amp;P)</h4><p>Home-office overhead recovery plus the contractor's markup, typically applied as a percentage to the direct cost + GC subtotal.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Contingency</h4><p>A reserve for known-unknowns within the defined scope of work; decreases in percentage as estimate class matures and design definition increases.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Allowance</h4><p>A placeholder dollar amount for scope that is real and included, but not yet fully defined (e.g., owner-selected finishes). Different from contingency, which covers risk, not undefined scope.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Work Breakdown Structure (WBS)</h4><p>A hierarchical decomposition of total project scope into deliverable-oriented work packages; the structural bridge between scope documents and the cost estimate.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Basis of Estimate (BOE)</h4><p>The documented assumptions, methodology, inclusions, and exclusions behind an estimate &mdash; the estimator's paper trail for what a number does and does not represent.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Scope Creep</h4><p>The uncontrolled expansion of project scope without corresponding adjustments to budget, schedule, or resources &mdash; often caused by undocumented direction or unclear scope boundaries.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="tab-activities" class="tab-content">
<div class="pw">
<h2>In-Class Activities</h2>

<div class="actbox">
<h3>Activity #1 &mdash; "Build the Estimate"</h3>
<div class="actmeta">
<div class="amitem">Format: <span>Small groups (3&ndash;4 students)</span></div>
<div class="amitem">Time: <span>15 minutes + debrief</span></div>
<div class="amitem">Tools: <span>Calculator / phone</span></div>
</div>
<p>Groups take off quantities from a simple scope sketch, price each line, and roll it up to a total price using the same build-up structure as the worked example. Debrief by comparing group totals and discussing where numbers diverged.</p>
</div>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Debrief Guide</div>Expect totals to vary &plusmn;10&ndash;15% across groups even using the same unit costs &mdash; that's the point. Ask which assumptions drove the difference (rounding on quantities, whether OH&amp;P was compounded or added, whether a group forgot GCs entirely). Reveal the instructor answer only after every group has reported a number.</div>

<div class="card">
<h4>Scenario &mdash; Activity #1</h4>
<p>Your crew must pour a new equipment pad: <strong>40 ft &times; 25 ft, 6" thick</strong>, with welded wire fabric reinforcing and a vapor barrier. Subgrade requires fine grading and compaction. Use the unit costs from the worked example (concrete $185/CY, WWF $0.55/SF, vapor barrier $0.28/SF, fine grade/compact $0.42/SF). Apply 8% general conditions, 12% OH&amp;P, and 5% contingency (Class 3 estimate), applied sequentially.</p>
<div class="ans">
<strong>Instructor Answer Key:</strong><br>
Area = 40 &times; 25 = 1,000 SF. Volume = 1,000 SF &times; (6/12 ft) = 500 CF &divide; 27 = <strong>18.52 CY</strong><br>
Concrete: 18.52 CY &times; $185 = <strong>$3,426</strong><br>
WWF: 1,000 SF &times; $0.55 = <strong>$550</strong><br>
Vapor barrier: 1,000 SF &times; $0.28 = <strong>$280</strong><br>
Fine grade/compact: 1,000 SF &times; $0.42 = <strong>$420</strong><br>
<strong>Direct Cost Subtotal = $4,676</strong><br>
&times; 1.08 (GCs) = $5,050 &rarr; &times; 1.12 (OH&amp;P) = $5,656 &rarr; &times; 1.05 (Contingency) = <strong>$5,939 Total Price</strong><br>
Accept answers within &plusmn;$25 for rounding on the CY conversion.
</div>
</div>

<div class="actbox" style="margin-top:32px;">
<h3>Activity #2 &mdash; "The Scope Gap"</h3>
<div class="actmeta">
<div class="amitem">Format: <span>Pairs</span></div>
<div class="amitem">Time: <span>7 minutes + 5 min debrief</span></div>
</div>
<p>An estimator discovers a missed scope item after the GMP is signed. Students work through the technical and ethical implications and decide the CM's next step.</p>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h4>Scenario</h4>
<p>You are the estimator/assistant PM on a $6.4M CM at Risk renovation. The GMP was signed three weeks ago with a $180,000 construction contingency. While preparing the buyout package, you discover the original estimate never priced the required fire pump room finishes (drywall, paint, door, and finish flooring) &mdash; a real scope item shown on the approved drawings but missed during takeoff. A subcontractor quote puts the cost at $22,000.</p>

<ol>
<li>Is this a contingency item, an allowance item, or a change order? Why?</li>
<li>Should you tell the owner? Why or why not?</li>
<li>What PMI Code of Ethics value(s) are most directly at stake?</li>
<li>What is your very next step?</li>
</ol>

</div>
<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br>
<strong>1.</strong> Neither an allowance nor a legitimate change order &mdash; it's an estimating error on scope that was already defined in the contract documents. The GC's contingency, not the owner's budget, should absorb it.<br><br>
<strong>2.</strong> Yes &mdash; disclose it. The owner is entitled to visibility into how their contingency (which exists to cover risk, not to backstop the GC's takeoff errors) is being consumed.<br><br>
<strong>3.</strong> Honesty (accurately representing why the cost exists) and Fairness (not quietly shifting an estimating error's cost onto a reserve the owner believes is protecting them from field risk).<br><br>
<strong>4.</strong> Document the discovery, notify the PM/project executive internally, prepare a written disclosure memo for the owner, and update the contingency log so the reserve's remaining balance and its causes stay transparent going forward.
</div>
</div>
</div>
