<div id="tab-ethics" class="tab-content">
<div class="pw">
<h2>Ethics, Leadership &amp; Professional Decision-Making</h2>
<p>Estimating and cost planning decisions are where a construction PM's professional judgment is tested most directly &mdash; bid deadlines, competitive pressure, and real money in an owner's contingency reserve.</p>

<h3>The PMI Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct</h3>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="card"><h4>Responsibility</h4><p>Owning the consequences of the numbers you produce, including admitting an error once found &mdash; even after the GMP is signed.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h4>Respect</h4><p>Treating the owner's money and trust with the same care you'd want extended to your own.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h4>Fairness</h4><p>Not padding contingency to quietly cover a known gap instead of disclosing it, and not exploiting ambiguous scope language to the owner's disadvantage.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h4>Honesty</h4><p>Representing an estimate's basis, exclusions, and confidence level accurately &mdash; never presenting a Class 4 number with Class 1 confidence to win an approval.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="callout cb"><strong>🔑 Source</strong>Project Management Institute, <em>Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct</em>. These four values apply directly to estimating: an estimator who quietly absorbs a missed scope item through contingency without disclosure violates Honesty and Fairness even if no policy is technically broken.</div>

<h3>Disclosure and Contingency Stewardship</h3>
<p>Contingency is uniquely vulnerable to quiet misuse because, unlike a change order, drawing it down doesn't require owner sign-off in most contracts. Common patterns: absorbing a takeoff error through contingency without telling the owner, using contingency to cover scope that should have been an allowance, or under-reporting the remaining balance to avoid a difficult conversation.</p>
<div class="callout cr"><strong>⚠ The Standard Is Disclosure, Not Just Intent</strong>PMI's ethical standard calls for proactive disclosure of what is consuming the reserve &mdash; regardless of whether the estimator believes the amount is "small enough not to matter." The owner's contingency exists to protect the owner from field risk, not to backstop the estimator's own errors invisibly.</div>

<h3>Leadership Under Bid-Day Pressure</h3>
<p>Estimating is one of the highest-pressure moments for professional integrity in a CM career: competitive deadlines, pressure to win work, and the temptation to under-disclose risk to make a number look better. A PM or lead estimator sets the tone for the whole team on whether shortcuts under deadline pressure are acceptable.</p>

<h3>A Simple Professional Decision-Making Framework</h3>
<div class="card">
<h4>Four Steps</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Identify the issue</strong> &mdash; name the gap or dilemma precisely, not vaguely</li>
<li><strong>Consider stakeholders and PMI's four values</strong> &mdash; who is affected, and which value is most at stake?</li>
<li><strong>Evaluate alternatives</strong> &mdash; what are the realistic options, including disclosure?</li>
<li><strong>Act and document</strong> &mdash; take the action and create a contemporaneous record of why</li>
</ol>
</div>

<h3>Discussion Questions</h3>

<ol>
<li>Is quietly absorbing a $5,000 estimating error through a $180,000 contingency "no big deal"? Why does PMI's standard treat it as a disclosure issue regardless of size?</li>
<li>How does an estimator document contingency drawdown so it withstands an owner audit or a dispute months later?</li>
<li>What's the difference between reasonable optimism in an early Class 5 estimate and presenting that number with false confidence &mdash; and why does the line matter ethically, not just technically?</li>
</ol>

<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Discussion Guide</div>Q1: Push students past "it's a small dollar amount so it's fine" &mdash; PMI's Fairness value is about the transparency and structural integrity of the reserve, not the size of any single item. Q2: Look for answers mentioning a contingency log with dated entries, cause codes, and running balance, shared with the owner at each pay application. Q3: Reasonable optimism means stating the accuracy range honestly (e.g., "-30%/+50%, Class 4"); false confidence means dropping the range or implying certainty the underlying design definition doesn't support &mdash; that's the line between professional judgment and misrepresentation.</div>
</div>
</div>
