<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 1 &mdash; Quantity Takeoff &amp; Pricing (15 pts, 5 pts each)</div>

<p>A contractor must estimate a concrete sidewalk: <strong>200 ft long, 5 ft wide, 4" thick</strong>. Unit costs: concrete $185/CY, forming $2.10/LF of edge, finishing/broom finish $0.65/SF. Calculate:</p>
<ol type="a">
<li>Concrete quantity in cubic yards and its extended cost</li>
<li>Forming cost (assume forming is required along both long edges only)</li>
<li>Finishing cost, and the direct cost subtotal for all three items</li>
</ol>

<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br>
a. Volume = 200 &times; 5 &times; (4/12) = 333.3 CF &divide; 27 = <strong>12.35 CY</strong> &times; $185 = <strong>$2,285</strong><br>
b. Edge length = 200 ft &times; 2 sides = 400 LF &times; $2.10 = <strong>$840</strong><br>
c. Area = 200 &times; 5 = 1,000 SF &times; $0.65 = <strong>$650</strong>. <strong>Direct Cost Subtotal = $2,285 + $840 + $650 = $3,775</strong><br>
Accept &plusmn;$15 for rounding.</div>
</div>

<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 2 &mdash; True/False with Justification (10 pts, 2 pts each)</div>

<p>State True or False and briefly explain your reasoning.</p>
<ol type="a">
<li>A Class 5 estimate is more accurate than a Class 2 estimate.</li>
<li>Contingency and allowance are interchangeable terms for the same budget reserve.</li>
<li>A well-documented Basis of Estimate should state what is excluded, not just what is included.</li>
<li>Markups such as GCs, OH&amp;P, and contingency should be added together as a single percentage and applied once to the direct cost.</li>
<li>A scope-alignment failure can exist even in a mathematically perfect estimate.</li>
</ol>

<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br>
a. <strong>FALSE.</strong> Class 5 is the least accurate (widest range); Class 1 is the most accurate. Lower class numbers mean more project definition and tighter accuracy.<br>
b. <strong>FALSE.</strong> Contingency covers risk/known-unknowns within defined scope; an allowance covers scope that is real but not yet fully defined. They serve different purposes and should be tracked separately.<br>
c. <strong>TRUE.</strong> Exclusions are just as important as inclusions &mdash; silence is often read by an owner as "included."<br>
d. <strong>FALSE.</strong> Markups compound sequentially against the running subtotal, not added together as one combined percentage of the original direct cost.<br>
e. <strong>TRUE.</strong> An estimate can be arithmetically flawless and still be wrong if it is priced against an incomplete or incorrect scope.</div>
</div>

<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 3 &mdash; Case Study (20 pts)</div>

<p>You are the estimator on a $9.5M ground-up office building, currently at 60% Construction Documents. The design team has issued the following updates since your last estimate:</p>
<ul>
<li>Structural: steel tonnage increased 8% due to a revised seismic design</li>
<li>MEP: owner added a rooftop generator (not previously scoped)</li>
<li>Architectural: lobby finish package upgraded from allowance-level to a specified stone finish</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Part A:</strong> For each item, identify whether it represents (i) a normal estimate refinement, (ii) new scope requiring a WBS update, or (iii) an allowance being resolved into a firm cost. Explain your reasoning.</p>
<p><strong>Part B:</strong> What estimate class should this project's estimate be classified as right now, and why?</p>
<p><strong>Part C:</strong> Describe the specific step you would take to keep the WBS and Basis of Estimate aligned with these three changes before the next estimate submission.</p>

<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key &mdash; Part A:</strong><br>
Steel tonnage increase: <strong>(i) normal refinement</strong> &mdash; same scope item, quantity refined as design develops.<br>
Rooftop generator: <strong>(ii) new scope</strong> &mdash; a physical system that did not exist in the prior scope/WBS; requires a new WBS work package and owner notification.<br>
Lobby finish upgrade: <strong>(iii) allowance resolved into firm cost</strong> &mdash; the allowance placeholder is replaced with a firm quote once the owner selects the finish; track as an allowance reconciliation, not a change order.<br><br>
<strong>Part B:</strong> <strong>Class 3 (Design Development / Budget)</strong> &mdash; at 60% CDs the project sits in the overlap zone between Class 3 and Class 2; accept either with correct reasoning, since estimate class is driven by deliverable maturity, not a single percentage cutoff.<br><br>
<strong>Part C:</strong> Update the affected WBS work packages, update the Basis of Estimate to document the reason for each change and its source, and formally reconcile the updated estimate against the WBS before resubmission so nothing is silently carried forward without a documented reason.</div>
</div>

