<h3>Estimate &amp; Scope Alignment Selection Checklist</h3>
<div class="callout cg"><strong>📥 Career Tool</strong>Print and use this checklist on any project that involves preconstruction estimating, GMP development, or design-milestone re-estimating. It documents your due diligence for the owner's file and for your own professional judgment record.</div>
<div class="card">
<h4>✅ CM Estimate &amp; Scope Alignment Checklist</h4>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 1:</strong> Confirm the estimate class matches the actual maturity of the design deliverables in hand &mdash; do not assume percent-complete equals estimate class.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 2:</strong> Walk the WBS against the scope narrative/OPR. Every WBS element should trace to a stated owner requirement.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 3:</strong> Walk the cost estimate against the WBS. Every WBS element should have a cost home; every cost line should map to a WBS element.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 4:</strong> Check interface/scope-boundary items explicitly &mdash; who furnishes vs. who installs, permit/testing costs, owner-furnished equipment hookups.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 5:</strong> Document a written exclusions/clarifications list on every estimate submission &mdash; silence gets read as "included."</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 6:</strong> Separate allowances (undefined scope) from contingency (risk reserve) in the estimate. Never blend the two.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 7:</strong> Confirm all markups (GCs, OH&amp;P, contingency) are applied sequentially against the running subtotal and clearly shown as separate line items.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 8:</strong> Track contingency drawdown by cause, not just by dollar amount, so the owner can see why the reserve is being consumed.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 9:</strong> Disclose discovered scope gaps to the owner in writing, even after GMP &mdash; do not silently absorb them through contingency without documentation.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 10:</strong> File the Basis of Estimate with the project record at every submission. It is the professional standard for what the number does and does not include.</div></div>
</div>

